{"title_page": "Linda Brookover", "text_new": "'''Linda Brookover''' is a US screenwriter,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2bd6571045|title=Linda Brookover|website=BFI}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.allocine.fr/personne/fichepersonne_gen_cpersonne=100986.html|title=Linda Brookover|website=AlloCin\u00e9}}</ref> film producer,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://blcklst.com/profile/linda-brookover |title=Linda Brookover}}</ref> essayist on film topics, especially the horror genre<ref>James Ursini, editor, ''Horror Film Reader,'' New York: Limelight, 2001, p. 317.</ref>  and [[film noir]].\n\n==Education==\n\nBrookover graduated from the [[University of Texas at Austin]] with a B.A. in Spanish. She has master's degrees in Education from both [[East Texas State University]] (now Texas A&M Commerce) and the [[University of California, Los Angeles]].<ref>''Film Noir Compendium'', Milwaukee: Applause, 2016, page 439</ref>\n\n==Writing==\nIn 1997 Brookover optioned the movie rights to the book ''[[Time at the Top]]'' by [[Edward Ormondroyd]] and wrote a screenplay that was produced the following year by [[Showtime Networks]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://playbackonline.ca/1998/06/15/21904-19980615/ |title=Playback: Quebec Scene |date=June 16, 1998}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0160986/|title=Time at the Top|via=www.imdb.com}}</ref> In 1998, Brookover was the production executive on the independent feature film ''[[Beat (2000 film)|Beat]]'', for which she co-wrote the ''ayahuasca'' scenes between the characters William S. Burroughs (Kiefer Sutherland) and his paid consort Lee (Sam Trammell).<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt0211941/|title=Beat (2000)|via=www.imdb.com}}</ref>\n\nIn 2001, she co-wrote and produced with [[Christopher Coppola]] the short horror spoof ''Texas Vampire Massacre'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt11272268/|title=Texas Vampire Massacre|via=www.imdb.com}}</ref> which provided \"delightful 'excerpts' from a supposed B&W regional horror\" as the fictional drive-in movie in Coppola's ''Bloodhead'' aka ''[[The Creature of the Sunny Side Up Trailer Park.]]''<ref>{{cite web |author=Dennis Harvey |url=https://variety.com/2004/film/reviews/bloodhead-1200534126/ |title=Bloodhead |work=Variety |date=April 6, 2004 |access-date=2019-11-10}}</ref> In 2002, she again co-produced with Coppola, the short Alzheimer's drama ''A Fish in the Desert,''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.imdb.com/title/tt11273776/|title=A Fish in the Desert|via=www.imdb.com}}</ref> which was based on her short story.\n\nBeginning in 1996 Brookover wrote a series of articles\u2014listed in the Bibliography\u2014about film noir and the \u201cpolitics\u201d of the horror genre.  During the same period she was an editor, interviewer, and essayist for the online Magazine ''OneWorld'', to which she contributed pieces on such varied subject as the Pueblo Revolts,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010702135248fw_/http://www.oneworldmagazine.org:80/focus/deserts/puebmain.htm|title=OneWorld Magazine: Deserts|date=July 2, 2001|website=web.archive.org}}</ref> American Indian activist Russell Means,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.dickshovel.com/intermeans.html|title=Means...|website=www.dickshovel.com}}</ref> ''ayahuasca'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20010303013403fw_/http://www.oneworldmagazine.org:80/tales/ayah/index.html|title=OneWorld Magazine - Ayahuasca, Power and Dreams|date=March 3, 2001|website=web.archive.org}}</ref> and the \u201cCrocodile Files\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030218180302fw_/http://www.oneworldmagazine.org:80/tales/crocs/index.html|title=OneWorld Magazine - The Crocodile Files|date=February 18, 2003|website=web.archive.org}}</ref><ref>Dan Wylie, London: Reaktion Books, 2013, p. 117.</ref> that featured one of the earliest interviews with the late \u201ccrocodile hunter [[Steve Irwin]].\n\n==Production==\nIn addition to ''Beat'' and the two short films, Brookover was executive producer on the independent features ''White Nights'' (2005) and ''Nightcomer'' (2013). She has also worked as a performer, assisted in pre-production or in various production capacities on various film and television projects from ''Men Seeking Women'' (1997) and ''Time at the Top'' to ''I Survived!'' (2000) and ''Ghost Phone'' (2011).\n\n==Bibliography==\n*\u201cWhat is this Thing Called Noir\u201d Essay in ''Film Noir Reader'', New York: Limelight, 1996, pages 260-273.\n*\u201cNaked Noir: Weegee and Film Noir,\u201d Featured article in ''The Noir Style'', New York: Overlook, pages 44\u201349.\n*\u201cMad Love is Strange: More Neo-noir Fugitives,\u201d Essay in ''Film Noir Reader 2'', New York, Limelight, 1999, pages 188-195.\n*\u201cBlanc et Noir: Crime as Art,\u201d Essay on ''The Public Eye'' in ''Film Noir Reader 2'', New York, Limelight, 1999, pages 216-221.\n*\u201cWhat Rough Beast? Insect Politics and ''The Fly''\u201d Essay in ''Horror Film Reader'', New York: Limelight, 2002, pages 236-245\n*\u201cVampire Politics and ''True Blood'',\u201d Featured article in ''The Vampire Film'', Limelight, 2010, pages 314-319.\n*\u201cThe Top Ten Reasons Why I Hate Zombies (and the Movies about Them),\u201d Featured article in ''The Zombie Film'', Milwaukee: Applause, 2012, pages 204-209.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|0111840}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brookover, Linda}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American women screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:University of Texas at Austin College of Liberal Arts alumni]]\n[[Category:Texas A&M University\u2013Commerce alumni]]\n[[Category:University of California, Los Angeles alumni]]\n", "text_old": "'''Linda Brookover''' is a US screenwriter,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bfi.org.uk/films-tv-people/4ce2bd6571045|title=Linda Brookover|website=BFI}}</